{"key":"post-12996870","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>12996870</id>\n<content>Fungi spores are killed by the time they reach 140F/60C.&amp;nbsp; This is why we pasteurize at this temperature.&amp;nbsp; Exactly 'what' temperature below 140F kills them is related to age of the spores, the amount of moisture content, and many other factors.&amp;nbsp; It's best to keep and store them at normal room temperature or below.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Vendors would be doing their customers in hot climates a service if they offered a 'hot weather' package, where the spore syringes would be shipped in an insulated box with a gel ice pack enclosed, via priority mail.&amp;nbsp; They'd have to charge extra for the package but it's a viable option when shipping to persons in horribly hot and miserable places.&amp;nbsp; I'm suffering through 75F heat and 12% humidity at the moment. &lt;img style=&quot;max-width:192px;height:auto;&quot; src=&quot;https://files.shroomery.org/smileys/lol.gif&quot; alt=&quot;:lol:&quot; title=&quot;:lol:&quot;/&gt;&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>12997112</next>\n<prev>12996209</prev>\n<first>12995528</first>\n<last>13001847</last>\n<when>1280872212</when>\n<utime>08/04/10 12:50 AM</utime>\n</post>"}